alist]], disappeared on 16 September 1970 and has not been seen since.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/09/22/archives/investigator-of-the-mafia-is-kidnapped-on-sicily.html|title=Investigator of the Mafia Is Kidnapped on Sicily|last=Times|first=Paul Hofmann Special To The New York|date=1970-09-22|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-08-23|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> |- |data-sort-value="1970-11-15"|1970 |[[Disappearance of Robin Graham|Robin Graham]] |18 (66 as o 2018) |After running out of gas on the [[Hollywood Freeway]], Robin Graham was last seen by [[California Highway Patrol]] (CHP) officers on 15 November 1970. The officer directed her to a [[callbox]] and later saw her speaking with a man beside her car. The circumstances of her disappearance resulted in CHP policies being changed to ensure the safety of stranded female motorists.<ref>[http://www.charleyproject.org/cases/g/graham_robin.html The Charley Project: Robin Ann Graham] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180101121341/http://www.charleyproject.org/cases/g/graham_robin.html# |date=1 January 2018 }} 5 February 2005.</ref> |- |data-sort-value="1971-11-24"|1971 |[[D. B. Cooper|D.B. Cooper]] | |Dan Cooper was the name, mistakenly reported in the media as D. B. Cooper, used by an unidentified man who hijacked a plane on 24 November 1971 and parachuted from it in mid-flight after extorting $200,000 in cash. No trace of him has ever been found, although some of the banknotes were found years later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://citizensleuths.com/db-cooper-what-you-need-to-know.html|title=D.B. Cooper: Everything you need to know in 5 minutes|website=citizensleuths.com|language=en-gb|access-date=2017-02-10}}</ref> |- |data-sort-value="1971-12-10"|1971 |[[Robert Durst#Other cases|Lynne Schulze]] |17 (64 {{as of|February 2018|lc=y}}) |Lynne Schulze, a student at [[Middlebury College]] in [[Vermont]], was last seen by one of her college friends on 10 December 1971 when she a